0:["LJgHqRHEXtboNpof0740S",[[["",{"children":["reverse-geocoding",{"children":["__PAGE__",{}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["reverse-geocoding",{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",["$","main",null,{"role":"main","className":"max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 py-12 prose-invert","children":["$","article",null,{"children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-electric-400 font-semibold","children":"Complete Guide"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"font-display text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mt-2 leading-[1.1]","children":"Reverse geocoding — turn a pair of GPS coordinates into a street address"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-4 text-lg text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["You have a latitude and longitude. You want the street, the neighborhood, the city, or even the building name. That translation — coordinates to a human-readable address — is called ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"reverse geocoding"}],". It powers ride-hailing apps, courier confirmations, photo-tagging, weather alerts by zip code, and the “city” field on every “find my location” page. This guide explains how it works, when it's accurate, when it isn't, and how to do it yourself."]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-6 glass rounded-2xl p-5 ring-1 ring-electric-400/30","children":["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong",null,{"className":"text-slate-100","children":"Quick way to try it."}]," Open"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"GetMyLocations"}]," ","and allow the location prompt. The reverse-geocoded result — city, region, and country — appears under your coordinates within a second."]}]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"What reverse geocoding is (and isn't)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Forward geocoding"}]," goes from text to coordinates: you type “1600 Amphitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA” and you get"," ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"37.4220, -122.0841"}],". That's what a search box in Google Maps does."]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Reverse geocoding"}]," is the opposite direction: you have the coordinates and want the text. It's harder than it sounds, because the same coordinate can be inside a building, inside a park, inside a body of water, or on a private road that has no official address."]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["Reverse geocoding is also not the same as ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"IP geolocation"}],". Reverse geocoding starts from real coordinates (typically from a GPS chip); IP geolocation guesses coordinates from a network address. Read more in our"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/ip-location-lookup","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"IP location lookup guide"}],"."]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"How it works under the hood"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Every reverse geocoder needs three things: a database of place boundaries (countries, regions, cities, postal codes), a database of street centerlines with house-number ranges, and an algorithm to pick the most specific answer that still contains your point."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The algorithm is roughly:"}],["$","ol",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-decimal list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Country."}]," A point-in-polygon test against world country borders. This is fast and almost always correct."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Region / state."}]," A second polygon test inside the country's subdivisions."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"City or town."}]," A third polygon test. Cities have fuzzy edges — one address may be inside a city legally and outside it for postal purposes, depending on which dataset you ask."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Street."}]," Find the nearest street segment within a small radius (usually 50–200 m). The segment has a left-side and right-side house-number range; interpolate."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"House number."}]," The interpolation gives a guess at the house number. It's often off by a few houses because streets number unevenly — gaps, corner lots, renumbered blocks."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Postal code."}]," A separate polygon dataset gives the zip / postcode."]}]]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Big providers (Google, Mapbox, HERE) add a points-of-interest layer on top: if your coordinate is inside a known building polygon, the response can include the building name (“Eiffel Tower”, “Sydney Opera House”) instead of just a street address. Open data sources like OpenStreetMap have the same idea but with patchier coverage."}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Find the address from a latitude / longitude pair"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Three practical ways to do it, in order of how much work they take:"}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-lg font-semibold mt-6 text-slate-100","children":"1. Use GetMyLocations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["The fastest way: paste your coordinates into the"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"main tool"}],", drop a manual pin, and the reverse-geocoded result appears next to it. The pipeline uses BigDataCloud first, with OpenStreetMap Nominatim as a fallback for areas BigDataCloud doesn't cover well."]}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-lg font-semibold mt-6 text-slate-100","children":"2. Use Google Maps directly"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["Type the coordinates straight into the Google Maps search box, separated by a comma:"," ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"48.8584, 2.2945"}],". Maps centers on the location and shows the address in the left panel. Useful for one-off checks but not bulk work."]}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-lg font-semibold mt-6 text-slate-100","children":"3. Hit an API directly"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"For programmatic work, two free options:"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"OpenStreetMap Nominatim"}],":"," ",["$","code",null,{"className":"bg-white/10 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-electric-400 text-sm","children":"https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org/reverse?lat=48.8584&lon=2.2945&format=json"}],". Free, no API key. Rate-limited to ~1 request per second — respect their fair-use policy."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"BigDataCloud"}],": free reverse-geocoding tier with no API key needed for client-side calls, decent global coverage. We use it as the default in GetMyLocations."]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Accuracy — when reverse geocoding gets it wrong"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Reverse geocoding is one of those features that's 95% correct and the remaining 5% is memorable. Common failure modes:"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"House number is off by a few."}]," Street centerline interpolation assumes evenly numbered houses, but real streets have gaps, irregular plots, and renumbered blocks. Off-by-two is normal in suburbs; off-by-ten happens in older neighborhoods."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Coordinates inside a building return the wrong building."}]," If two buildings are close together and the polygons overlap or are slightly mislabeled, the API may return whichever was indexed first."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Rural areas have no street address at all."}]," A coordinate in the middle of a forest, on a dirt track, or on a long-frontage farm will return only a town and region. There's nothing more specific to return."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Bodies of water."}]," Reverse geocoding the middle of a lake or sea typically returns a description like “Pacific Ocean” rather than a street address."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"International disagreements."}]," Contested borders (Kashmir, Crimea, Western Sahara) appear differently depending on which provider's map of the world you query."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Newly built streets."}]," A street built in the last 6–12 months may not be in the provider's database yet."]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Typical uses for reverse geocoding"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Ride-hailing and delivery confirmations."}]," “Driver is at 24 Main St” comes from reverse-geocoding the driver's GPS in real time."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Photo metadata."}]," Apple Photos, Google Photos, and Lightroom all reverse-geocode embedded EXIF GPS into city / country tags so you can browse photos by place."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Weather alerts."}]," Severe-weather pushes are targeted by zip code; the phone reverse-geocodes its GPS to figure out which zip to subscribe to."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Insurance and emergency response."}]," A 911/112 dispatcher reverse-geocodes an inbound AML coordinate to get a confirm-able address."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Marketing and analytics."}]," Aggregated GPS pings reverse-geocoded to city level power footfall reports, retail catchment studies, and traffic analytics."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Hiking and trip logs."}]," Turning a GPX track's coordinates into named places gives you a journal entry rather than a list of numbers."]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Drop a pin on the map and reverse-geocode it"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["The most visual way to do reverse geocoding is to drop a pin. Open"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"GetMyLocations"}],", switch to manual input mode, type or paste any coordinates, and the map flies to that point with a pin. The address text appears in the dashboard underneath, with separate fields for city, region, country, and (where available) the nearest street."]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["For a refresher on coordinate formats before you paste anything in, see our"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/gps-coordinates-finder","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"GPS coordinates finder guide"}]," ","and the ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/decimal-degrees-converter","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"decimal degrees converter"}],"."]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-10 border-white/10"}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold","children":"Privacy and what we (don't) keep"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["When you reverse-geocode through GetMyLocations, the coordinates are sent in real time to a third-party API to produce the address — we don't cache or store them on a server we operate. The third parties (BigDataCloud, OpenStreetMap Nominatim) have their own privacy practices, summarized in our"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/privacy-policy","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"Privacy Policy"}],"."]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-10","children":"Related guides"}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"mt-3 space-y-2 text-slate-300/90 list-disc list-inside","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/gps-coordinates-finder","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"GPS coordinates finder — complete guide"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/decimal-degrees-converter","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"Decimal degrees converter (DD ↔ DMS)"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/ip-location-lookup","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"IP location lookup — complete guide"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/fix-location-not-working","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline","children":"Fix location not working — troubleshooting"}]}]]}]]}]}],null],null],null]},[null,["$","$L3",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children","reverse-geocoding","children"],"error":"$undefined","errorStyles":"$undefined","errorScripts":"$undefined","template":["$","$L4",null,{}],"templateStyles":"$undefined","templateScripts":"$undefined","notFound":"$undefined","notFoundStyles":"$undefined"}]],null]},[[[["$","link","0",{"rel":"stylesheet","href":"/_next/static/css/39f772c519388c7e.css","precedence":"next","crossOrigin":"$undefined"}]],["$","html",null,{"lang":"en","dir":"ltr","children":[["$","head",null,{"children":[["$","link",null,{"rel":"preconnect","href":"https://fonts.googleapis.com"}],["$","link",null,{"rel":"preconnect","href":"https://fonts.gstatic.com","crossOrigin":""}],["$","link",null,{"rel":"stylesheet","href":"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700;800&family=Sora:wght@600;700;800&display=swap"}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"GetMyLocations\",\"url\":\"https://getmylocations.com/\",\"logo\":\"https://getmylocations.com/icon-512.png\",\"sameAs\":[]}"}}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"WebSite\",\"name\":\"GetMyLocations\",\"url\":\"https://getmylocations.com/\",\"potentialAction\":{\"@type\":\"SearchAction\",\"target\":\"https://getmylocations.com/?q={search_term_string}\",\"query-input\":\"required name=search_term_string\"}}"}}],["$","script",null,{"async":true,"src":"https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?client=ca-pub-2240955720087760","crossOrigin":"anonymous"}]]}],["$","body",null,{"children":[["$","$L5",null,{}],["$","$L3",null,{"parallelRouterKey":"children","segmentPath":["children"],"err